==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Cadge
<hw>Cadge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Cadged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Cadging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Scot.
<ets>cache</ets>, <ets>caich</ets>, <ets>cadge</ets>, to toss, drive,
OE. <ets>cachen</ets> to drive, catch, <ets>caggen</ets> to bind, or
perh. E. <ets>cage</ets>. Cf. <er>Cadger</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To carry, as a burden.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. &
Scot.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hawk or peddle, as fish, poultry, etc.</def>
<mark>[Prov.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To intrude or live on another meanly; to beg.</def>
<mark>[Prov. or Slang, Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Wright.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cadge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Cadge
<hw>Cadge</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. 2d <er>Cadger</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Hawking)</fld> <def>A circular frame on which cadgers carry hawks
for sale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cadger</ent>⟦br⟧
